=== Notable flights ===
[[File:SpaceX Falcon 9 launch with COTS Demo Flight 1 (low quality).ogv|thumb|upright=1.5|SpaceX Falcon 9 launch with COTS Demo Flight 1]]
[[File:ORBCOMM-2 First-Stage Landing (23271687254).jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|[[Falcon 9 flight 20]] historic [[Falcon 9 first-stage landing tests|first-stage landing]] at [[Cape Canaveral Space Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Landing Zones 1 and 2|Landing Zone 1]], on 21 December 2015]]

* Flight 1, [[Dragon Spacecraft Qualification Unit]] — 4 June 2010, first flight of Falcon 9 and first test of [[SpaceX Dragon|Dragon]],
* Flight 3, [[SpaceX COTS Demo Flight 2|Dragon C2+]] — first cargo delivery to the [[International Space Station]],
* Flight 4, [[SpaceX CRS-1|CRS-1]] — first operational cargo mission to the [[International Space Station|ISS]], and the first demonstration of the rocket's engine-out capability due to the failure of a first-stage [[SpaceX Merlin|Merlin]] engine,
* Flight 6, [[CASSIOPE]] — first [[Falcon 9 v1.1|v1.1 rocket]], first launch from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base|Vandenberg AFB]], first attempt at [[Falcon 9 first-stage landing tests|propulsive return of the first stage]],
* Flight 7, [[SES-8]] — first launch to [[Geosynchronous transfer orbit]] (GTO), first non-governmental payload,
* Flight 9, [[SpaceX CRS-3|CRS-3]] — added landing legs, first [[Falcon 9 first-stage landing tests#Ocean touchdown attempts|fully controlled descent and vertical ocean touchdown]],
* Flight 15, [[Deep Space Climate Observatory]] (DSCOVR) — first mission injecting spacecraft into [[Lagrange point|L1]] point,
* Flight 19, [[SpaceX CRS-7|CRS-7]] — total loss of mission due to structural failure and helium overpressure in the second stage,
* [[Falcon 9 flight 20|Flight 20]], [[Orbcomm (satellite)|Orbcomm OG-2]] — first vertical landing of an orbital-class rocket booster,
* Flight 23, [[SpaceX CRS-8|CRS-8]] — first [[Vertical takeoff, vertical landing|landing vertically]] achieved on an [[autonomous spaceport drone ship]] at sea,
* [[AMOS-6]] — total vehicle and payload loss prior to [[static fire]] test (would have been Flight 29),
* Flight 30, [[SpaceX CRS-10|CRS-10]] — first launch from [[Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39A|LC-39A]] at the [[Kennedy Space Center]],
* Flight 32, [[SES-10]] — first reflight of a previously flown orbital class booster ([[List of Falcon 9 first-stage boosters|B1021]], previously used for [[SpaceX CRS-8]]), first recovery of a fairing,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/30/15117096/spacex-launch-reusable-rocket-success-falcon-9-landing|title=SpaceX makes aerospace history with successful launch and landing of a used rocket |last=Grush|first=Loren|date=30 March 2017|publisher=The Verge|access-date=2 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330232640/http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/30/15117096/spacex-launch-reusable-rocket-success-falcon-9-landing|archive-date=30 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=fairing-recovery/>
* Flight 41, [[Boeing X-37|X-37B]] [[USA-277|OTV-5]] — first launch of a [[spaceplane]],
* Flight 54 [[Bangabandhu Satellite-1|Bangabandhu-1]] — the first flight of the [[Falcon 9 Full Thrust Block 5|Block 5]] version,
* Flight 58 [[Telstar 19V]] — heaviest communications satellite delivered to GEO, at the time,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2018/07/spacex-falcon-9-telstar-19v-launch/|title=SpaceX Falcon 9 sets new record with Telstar 19V launch from SLC-40|date=21 July 2018|website=nasaspaceflight.com|access-date=2 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722100004/https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2018/07/spacex-falcon-9-telstar-19v-launch/|archive-date=22 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn-ua|Jupiter 3/EchoStar XXIV has a larger mass, when comparing both initial mass (~9,200 kg vs. 7,076 kg) and dry mass (5,817 kg vs. 3,031 kg)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/jupiter-3.htm|title=Jupiter 3 / EchoStar 24|work=Gunter's Space Page|author=Krebs, Gunter D.}}</ref>}}
* Flight 69 [[Crew Dragon Demo-1]] — first launch of the [[SpaceX Dragon 2|Crew Dragon]] (did not carry astronauts),
* Flight 72, [[RADARSAT Constellation]] — the most valuable commercial payload put into orbit,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ralph|first1=Eric|title=SpaceX Falcon 9 bids temporary goodbye to West Coast in launch and landing photos|date=13 June 2019 |url=https://www.teslarati.com/spacex-falcon-9-california-radarsat-launch-in-photos/|publisher=Teslarati|access-date=13 June 2020|archive-date=13 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200613060243/https://www.teslarati.com/spacex-falcon-9-california-radarsat-launch-in-photos/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ralph|first1=Eric|title=SpaceX's Falcon 9 sticks foggy booster recovery at California landing zone|date=12 June 2019 |url=https://www.teslarati.com/spacex-falcon-9-radarsat-launch-watch-live/|publisher=Teslarati|access-date=13 June 2020|archive-date=17 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117011725/https://www.teslarati.com/spacex-falcon-9-radarsat-launch-watch-live/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Launch of SpaceX Falcon 9 Block 5 with RADARSAT Constellation|url=https://www.spacetv.net/live/launch-of-spacex-falcon-9-block-5-with-radarsat-constellation/|publisher=Spacetv|access-date=13 June 2020|archive-date=2 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210302070936/https://www.spacetv.net/live/launch-of-spacex-falcon-9-block-5-with-radarsat-constellation/|url-status=live}}</ref>
* Flight 81 — a [[Starlink]] launch, was a successful flight, but had the first recovery failure of a previously flown and recovered booster,
* Flight 83 — a successful [[Starlink]] launch, saw the first failure of a Merlin 1D first-stage engine during ascent, and the second ascent engine failure on the rocket following [[SpaceX CRS-1|CRS-1]] on flight 4,
* Flight 85, [[Crew Dragon Demo-2]] — the first crewed launch of the Crew Dragon, carrying two astronauts,
* Flight 98, [[Crew-1]] — the first crewed operational launch of the Crew Dragon, holding the record for the longest spaceflight by a U.S. crew vehicle,
* Flight 101, [[CRS-21]] — the first launch of the Cargo Dragon 2, an uncrewed variant of the Crew Dragon,
* Flight 106, Transporter-1 — the first dedicated smallsat rideshare launch arranged by SpaceX{{efn-ua|The first dedicated smallsat rideshare launch was flight 64, [[2018 in spaceflight#December|SSO-A: SmallSat Express]], arranged by [[Spaceflight, Inc.]] (a division [[Spaceflight Industries]] at the time). It carried two [[SHERPA (space tug)|SHERPA dispencers]] and nothing else.}}, set the record of the most satellites launched on a single launch with 143 satellites, surpassing the previous record of 108 satellites held by the November 17, 2018 launch of an [[Antares (rocket)|Antares]],
* Flight 108 — a routine [[Starlink]] launch which experienced early shut-down of a first-stage Merlin 1D engine during ascent due to damage, but still delivered the payload to the target orbit,
* Flight 126, [[Inspiration4]] — the first orbital spaceflight of an all-private crew,
* Flight 129, [[Double Asteroid Redirection Test|DART]] — first planetary defenses mission against [[near-Earth objects]],
* Flight 134, [[CRS-24]] — the 100th successful vertical landing of an orbital-class rocket, on the sixth anniversary of the first landing in 2015,
* Flight 228 — The 200th consecutive successful Falcon 9 mission.
* Flight 232 — The 200th overall successful booster landing.
* Flight 236 — First launch with a fairing half flying for the tenth time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Romera |first1=Alejandro Alcantarilla |title=SpaceX record-breaking first half of 2023 following Starlink launch |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2023/06/starlink-5-12-launch/ |work=NASASpaceFlight.com |date=23 June 2023}}</ref>
* Flight 239 — [[List of Falcon 9 first-stage boosters#Booster_1058|B1058]] becomes the first Falcon 9 booster to fly and land 16 times. This was preceded by certification of boosters to fly up to 20 times, double the initial goal.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Stephen |title=SpaceX is stretching the lifetime of its reusable Falcon 9 boosters |url=https://arstechnica.com/space/2023/07/spacex-launches-its-fleet-leading-rocket-booster-for-record-16th-time/ |access-date=22 September 2023 |work=Ars Technica |date=10 July 2023 |language=en-us}}</ref>

